mocratic accountability and popular engagement in the making of foreign policy. Based on extensive archival research, The British people and the League of Nations offers a vivid account of this popular League consciousness and in so doing reveals the vibrant character of associational life between the wars.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aHISTORY / Europe / Great Britain / General.2bisacsh  aLeague of Nations.  acivic ritual.  ademocratic accountability.  ainternational co-operation.  amember-states.  anew world order.  apeace.  apolitical protest.  apopular education.  avoluntary societies.1 aMcCarthy, Helen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez978311128363040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978184779428440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781847794284423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781847794284/original  a978-3-11-128363-0  Manchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagec1986d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles